opendcl-conformance — scenario corpus, spec chapter, coverage tracker
=====================================================================

See also: opendcl.plan, opendcl-runtime-core.issue,
opendcl-controls.issue, opendcl-host-pickers.issue.

Context
-------

OpenDCL's surface is large (~300 AutoLISP functions, ~30 controls,
synchronous + event paths). The DCL work showed that declarative
scenarios (autolisp-file-compat style) are how you keep a vendor-
sensitive surface honest. This issue captures the longitudinal
*quality* work that runs alongside every implementation phase:

  - a declarative conformance corpus that grows per scenario;
  - an autolisp-spec chapter that documents the OpenDCL surface
    clautolisp actually implements;
  - a coverage tracker that maps upstream's ~300 builtins to
    {implemented, stubbed, out-of-scope, unknown}.

In scope
--------

  1. Corpus layout. Mirror `autolisp-file-compat/scenarios/`:

         clautolisp/autolisp-opendcl/scenarios/
             lifecycle/      load, show, close, multi-form
             properties/    get / set per control class
             events/        click, selection-changed, focus-lost
             pickers/       entity / layer / block / colour
             projects/      whole-project round-trips from upstream
                            Samples/

     Each scenario is a `.sexp` declaration: a `:name`,
     `:classification` (:portable, :opendcl-only, :divergent), a
     project to load, an event script to inject, an expected
     wire-trace fragment, and expected AutoLISP-visible results.

  2. Runner. Either:
       (a) extend `autolisp-file-compat/tools/run-file-compat/` to
           speak the OpenDCL `:kind :opendcl` scenario shape, or
       (b) add a sibling
           `clautolisp/autolisp-opendcl/tools/run-opendcl-compat/`.
     Decision at ticket-pickup time; (a) reuses more
     infrastructure but couples the file-compat surface to
     OpenDCL semantics. Lean (b) by default.

     The runner uses a *mock renderer* in CI (no GUI required);
     a `--real-renderer` flag drives the actual
     `clautolisp-gui-qt` under Xvfb for the smoke subset.

  3. autolisp-spec chapter. Add
     `autolisp-spec/documentation/opendcl-surface.org` with:
       - per-control entries (properties, events, status);
       - per-builtin entries (`dcl_*` functions, arguments,
         return shape, status);
       - the wire-protocol catalogue (cross-link to
         `opendcl-wire-protocol.issue`);
       - vendor parity notes when upstream OpenDCL on Windows
         behaves differently from our implementation.

  4. Coverage tracker. A small CL tool, sibling to
     `clautolisp/tools/builtins-coverage`, that:
       - reads upstream OpenDCL's exported `dcl_*` function list
         (research up-front: it's enumerated in their LSP file
         under `lsp/`);
       - cross-checks against `clautolisp/autolisp-opendcl`'s
         installed builtins;
       - emits a status table (implemented / stubbed / missing).
       - hooks into `make builtins-coverage` (or a sibling
         `make opendcl-coverage`).

  5. CI. Wire the corpus runner into `make test` (mock-renderer
     mode) and add an optional GitLab-CI lane that runs the
     real-renderer subset under Xvfb.

Out of scope
------------

  - Snapshot-image comparison of rendered widgets. Too fragile
    cross-platform; defer.
  - Side-by-side execution against real AutoCAD / BricsCAD. The
    runner *templates* should be designed to support it (the
    file-compat runner already does this for filesystem
    scenarios), but the actual cross-vendor capture lane is
    follow-up work.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - At least one scenario per category in §1 above lands as the
    other tickets ship their pieces.
  - autolisp-spec opendcl-surface.org compiles cleanly and is
    linked from the master spec TOC.
  - Coverage tracker output committed under a known path so
    progress is visible.
  - `make opendcl-conformance` (or whatever target name is chosen)
    runs the mock-renderer corpus from scratch and exits non-zero
    on any regression.

Notes
-----

Treat this issue as a *backbone* that the other tickets feed into
— don't try to finish it standalone. Every other ticket in the
OpenDCL plan should land at least one scenario and one spec entry
as part of its acceptance criteria.
